The '''Micronesian myzomela''' ('''''Myzomela rubratra'''''), also known as the '''micronesian honeyeater''', is a species of [[honeyeater]].

== Taxonomy ==
The Micronesian myzomela was first [[formally described]] by [[René Lesson]] in 1827 as ''Cinnyris rubrater''.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Cuvier |first=Frédéric |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/42219 |title=Dictionnaire des sciences naturelles, dans lequel on traite méthodiquement des différens êtres de la nature, considérés soit en eux-mêmes, d'après l'état actuel de nos connoissances, soit relativement à l'utilité qu'en peuvent retirer la médecine, l'agriculture, le commerce et les artes. Suivi d'une biographie des plus célèbres naturalistes ... |date=1827 |publisher=F. G. Levrault, Le Normant |volume=50 |location=[[Strasbourg]] and [[Paris]] |pages=50-51 |language=fr |trans-title=Dictionary of the natural sciences, in which one methodically treats of the different beings of nature, considered either in themselves, according to the current state of our knowledge, or relatively to the utility that medicine, agriculture, commerce, and the arts can derive from them. Followed by a biography of the most celebrated naturalists... |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.42219}}</ref><!-- The first volume was published in 1816, vol. 50 was published 1827. --> In 1835 it was designated ''Certhia'' ''cardinalis''<ref>{{cite journal |last=von Kittlitz |first=Heinrich |author-link=Heinrich von Kittlitz |date=1834 |title=Über einige noch unbeschriebene Vögel Insel Luzon, den Carolinen und den Marianen |trans-title=On Some Undescribed Birds from the Island of Luzon, the Carolines, and the Marianas |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/37113040 |journal=Mémoire Présentés à L'Académie Impériale des Sciences de Saint Pétersbourg par Divers Savans et dans ses Assemblées |language=German |issue=2 |pages=1-9 |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]]|issn=1560-0106}}</ref> and moved a year later to ''Cinnyris cardinalis'' by [[Heinrich von Kittlitz]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=von Kittlitz |first=Heinrich |author-link=Heinrich von Kittlitz |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/38074 |title=Voyage autour du monde, exécuté par ordre de Sa Majesté l'empereur Nicolas Ier, sur la corvette Le Séniavine, dans les années 1826, 1827, 1828 et 1829 / par Frédéric Lutké. Tome troisième contenant les travaux de mm. les naturalistes, rédigé par Alexandre Postels |last2=Postels |first2=Alexander |author-link2=Alexander Postels |date=1836 |editor-last=Lütke |editor-first=Friedrich Benjamin von |editor-link=Friedrich Benjamin von Lütke |volume=3 |location=Paris |language=fr |trans-title=Voyage Around the World, undertaken by order of His Majesty Emperor Nicholas I aboard the corvette *Le Séniavine*, in the years 1826, 1827, 1828, and 1829 / by Frédéric Lutké. Volume III, containing the works of the naturalists, compiled by Alexandre Postels |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.38074|pages=285|via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]]}}</ref> In 1850, [[Charles Lucien Bonaparte]] became the first to place it in its current genus, ''Myzomela'', assigning it the [[specific epithet]] ''sanguinolenta''<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bonaparte |first=Charles-Lucien |author-link=Charles Lucien Bonaparte |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/70841 |title=Conspectus generum avium |date=1850 |publisher=E.J. Brill |location=Lugduni Batavorum |language=la |trans-title=A look at the types of birds |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.70841|pages=394|via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]]}}</ref> (from [[Classical Latin|Latin]] ''sanguis'', meaning "blood".)<ref>{{Cite web |editor-last=Jobling |editor-first=J. A. |title=The Key to Scientific Names |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/key-to-scientific-names/search |access-date=2026-03-25 |website=[[Birds of the World]] |language=en}}</ref> It was then renamed by [[Gustav Hartlaub]], first in 1852 as ''M. rubrater'',<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hartlaub |first=Gustav |date=1852 |title=R. Titian Peale's Vögel der United States Exploring Expedition |trans-title=R. Titian Peale's Birds of the United States Exploring Expedition |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/13707502 |journal=Archiv für Naturgeschichte |language=de |issue=188 |pages=109 |via=[[Biodiversity Heritage Library]]|author-link=Gustav Hartlaub}}</ref> then in 1854 as ''M. rubratra'',<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Hartlaub |first=Gustav |date=1854 |title=Zur Ornithologie Oceanien's |trans-title=On the Ornithology of Oceania |url=https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02006771 |journal=Journal für Ornithologie |language=de |volume=2 |issue=2 |pages=169 |doi=10.1007/BF02006771 |issn=1439-0361|author-link=Gustav Hartlaub}}</ref> which it has kept since.<ref name=":0" /> In 1932, [[Ernst Mayr]] deemed it [[conspecific]] with the [[cardinal myzomela]],<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Mayr |first=Ernst |author-link=Ernst Mayr |date=1932 |title=Birds collected during the Whitney South Sea Expedition. 18. Notes on Meliphagidae from Polynesia and the Solomon Islands. |url=https://digitallibrary.amnh.org/items/1f9d882b-7857-456b-aa67-7234d403e582 |journal=[[American Museum Novitates]] |issue=516 |pages=19}}</ref> however it is now recognized by most major authorities as its own species.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Lepage |first=Denis |title=Myzomela rubratra (Micronesian Myzomela) |url=https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?avibaseid=45B5DE59C6981DB5 |access-date=2026-03-25 |website=[[Avibase|Avibase, the World Bird Database]]}}</ref> Its specific epithet, ''rubratra'', is a compound of Latin ''rubra'' and ''atra'', meaning "red" and "black" respectively.{{sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Systematics}} 7 subspecies of the Micronesian myzomela are recognized.<ref name=":0" />

{{Subspecies bullet list item|scientific name=M. r. rubratra|describer last name=Lesson|year described=1827|description= The nominate subspecies. Found on [[Kosrae]] of the [[Caroline Islands]]. The adult male's body is almost entirely scarlet or scarlet-red, excluding the thighs and the [[lore (anatomy)|lores]] (the area between the eye and nostrils), which are black. The adult female's plumage is similar, although she is smaller in size, and her coloring is duller. The juvenile of both sexes are reminiscent of the adults, although it is duller and of a lighter tone in comparision, and its coloring is not as vivid.{{sfn |Baker|1951 |p = 305-306}}|describer name=René Lesson}}{{Subspecies bullet list item|scientific name=M. r. dichromata|describer last name=Wetmore|year described=1919|description= Found on [[Pohnpei]] of the [[Caroline Islands]]. The adult male strongly resembles that of the nominate subspecies, except that the black markings on his lores and below the eye are more substantial. and the tips of his colored feathers are brighter. The adult female is similar to the nominate, though the extent of her red plumage is greatly reduced. Her chin, throat, and the underside of her tail are reddish. The rest of her body is colored varying shades of brownish-gray, occasionally with reddish patches. The juvenile male resembles the adult, except that his scarlet coloring is less vivid and is thinner on his rump, forehead, underparts, and the base of his tail. The red coloring is usually absent from his neck and the top of his head. The juvenile female is also like the adult, but her scarlet coloring is thinner and only visible on her back, rump, underpartds, and the base of her tail.{{sfn |Baker|1951 |p = 307-308}} Its name comes from Latin ''dichromata'', meaning two-colored.{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}}|describer name=Alexander Wetmore|para=x}}{{Subspecies bullet list item|scientific name=M. r. major|describer last name=Bonaparte|year described=1854|description=Found on [[Chuuk Lagoon]] of the [[Caroline Islands]]. Both sexes look similar to nominate. The adult male's feathers are lighter on the tips. The adult female's underparts are colored a brighter scarlet-red. The juvenile male looks similar to the adult female, except the feathers on his head and neck have less scarlet coloring on the tips. The juvenile female resembles the nominate's juvenile female, except that her upperparts are grayer and her underparts are darker.{{sfn |Baker|1951 |p = 308-309}} Its name comes from Latin ''major'', meaning greater or larger.{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}}|describer name=Charles Lucien Bonaparte|para=x}}{{Subspecies bullet list item|scientific name=M. r. kurodai|describer last name=Momiyama|year described=1922|description=Found on [[Yap]] of the [[Caroline Islands]]. The adult male resembles the adult male ''M. r. saffordi'', although his leg is shorter, and his plumage is less orange-hued. The adult female's upperparts are a dark green-brown. Her underparts are paler but otherwise similar, though her breast and abdomen may be yellow-gray. Her head, rump, and lower back, along with her entire frontside, are all tinged scarlet-red.{{sfn |Baker|1951 |p = 312}} It is named after [[Nagamichi Kuroda]], a Japanese ornithologist.{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}}|describer name=Tokutaro Momiyama|para=x|link=x}}{{Subspecies bullet list item|scientific name=M. r. kobayashii|describer last name=Momiyama|year described=1922|description=Found on the islands of [[Palau]].{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}} The adult male resembles nominate; however he is smaller and the scarlet coloring on his body is darker, more so than that of any other subspecies. The adult female resembles the female ''M. r. dichromata'', although her abdomen, the underside of her tail feathers, and her "armpits" ([[axillary feathers]]) are rust-gray. Unlike all other subspecies, the top of her head is only partly colored red. The juvenile male resembles the adult except for his lighter and scantier scarlet-red coloring. His wings and tail are green-brown, and the underside of his tail is off-gray. The juvenile female is like the adult, just that her scarlet-red coloring is paler and her underparts are tinted red.{{sfn |Baker|1951 |p = 313-314}} It is named after Keisuke Kobayashi, Sr, a Japanese [[ornithologist]] and [[oologist]].{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}}|describer name=Tokutaro Momiyama|para=x|link=x}}{{Subspecies bullet list item|scientific name=M. r. asuncionis|describer last name=Salomonsen|year described=1966|description=Found from [[Anatahan]] to [[Asuncion Island|Asuncion]] of the [[Northern Mariana Islands]]. All ages and genders are visually identical to ''saffordi''.<!-- in BOW, the description for asuncionis and saffordi are identical. -->{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}}|describer name=Finn Salomonsen|para=x}}{{Subspecies bullet list item|scientific name=M. r. saffordi|describer last name=Wetmore|year described=1917|description=Found on the southern islands of the [[Northern Mariana Islands]], namely [[Rota, Northern Mariana Islands|Rota]], [[Aguiguan]], [[Tinian]], and [[Saipan]]. Formerly found on [[Guam]], before its extinction there.{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}} Both sexes resemble nominate, with minor differences. The adult male is slightly smaller and his scarlet-red coloring is more orange. Unlike the other subspecies, the male ''saffordi'''s wings and tail are tinted olive. The adult female is also smaller and paler in color. Her upperparts are dark green-gray occasionally mottled with scarlet, and the underside of her tail and her abdomen are red-gray. She can be differentiated from other subspecies by her scarlet-tipped feathers on the top of her head, and the dark olive coloring on the edges of her tail feathers.{{sfn |Baker|1951 |p = 310}} It is named after [[William Edwin Safford]], a [[botanist]].{{sfn |Craig |Pyle |2026 |loc=Systematics § Subspecies}}|describer name=Alexander Wetmore|para=x}}

== Description ==
The Micronesian myzomela is a small [[honeyeater]] measuring 13 cm in length.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Higgins |first=Peter J. |last2=Christidis |first2=Les |last3=Ford |first3=Hugh |date=2020 |title=Micronesian Myzomela (Myzomela rubratra), version 1.0 |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/micmyz1/1.0/introduction |journal=Birds of the World |language=en |doi=10.2173/bow.micmyz1.01 |issn=2771-3105}}</ref> The sexes [[Sexual dimorphism|differ]] in size and appearance: The adult male weighs 15 g (range 12.7{{Endash}}18 g){{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Measurements § Mass}} and has a 72 mm [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]], a 13 mm bill, a 55 mm tail, and a 21 mm {{Birdgloss|tarsus}},{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Measurements § Linear Measurements}} and the adult female is smaller, weighing 12.7 g (range 10.4{{Endash}}15 g){{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Measurements § Mass}} and with a wing chord measuring 66 mm, a 11 mm bill, a 55 mm tail, and a 20 mm tarsus.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Measurements § Linear Measurements}} In both sexes and at all ages, the [[Beak|bill]] is distinctly curved downwards. It is colored brown with a yellow base in juveniles, darkening with age, becoming completely black in adults. Similarly, the {{Birdgloss|gape}} also darkens with age, starting bright yellow and becoming black in adults. The [[tongue]] and interior of the mouth are bright yellow.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Bare Parts § Bill and Gape}} Its iris is dark brown,{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Bare Parts § Iris and Facial Skin}} and its toes and tarsi are scaly and dark brown, with the undersides of the feet being dull yellow.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Bare Parts § Tarsi and Toes}}

The female has dusky brown [[Retrices|tail]] and [[wing feathers]] fringed with olive, and a predominantly black or brown body with scarlet-red patches. The male is similar, though his patches are more vermilion and he lacks any brown coloring. The extent and placement of the patches vary between subspecies in both sexes.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Plumage § Definitive Basic Plumage}} Juveniles of both genders are much browner compared to adults and have little to none red patches.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Plumage § Juvenile (First Basic) Plumage}}

=== Vocalizations ===
{{Birdsong|url=https://xeno-canto.org/species/Myzomela-rubratra|species=the Micronesian myzomela}}
The Micronesian myzomela has a complex [[Dawn chorus (birds)|dawn song]] that differs from its vocalizations later in the day.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Sounds and Vocal Behavior § Vocalizations § Vocal Array}} On [[Kosrae]], the song begins before there is enough light to see the bird and lasts until it is visible (about 25 minutes); it has been described as sounding like multiple birds singing in unison. The song consists of a continuous stream of trilled whistles and phrases, which may be transcribed as "cheeky cheeky can't beat the heat," "too sweet to eat," or "she eats a pizza".<ref name=":1" /> The dawn song on [[Yap]] and [[Pohnpei]] is similar but slower and less slurred.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Sounds and Vocal Behavior § Vocalizations § Vocal Array}} Later in the day, the Korsae bird's song is short and highly variable, usually consisting of two slurred notes ("seee-oo SEET" or "schweer cheap-beer") and one emphatic note. The calls have been described as "rather uninteresting" but are more variable still, and include sharp "tseep!" notes that may be repeated, short buzzy calls, and rough scolds.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal |last=Hayes |first=Floyd E. |last2=Pratt |first2=H. Douglas |last3=Cianchini |first3=Carlos J. |date=2016 |title=The Avifauna of Kosrae, Micronesia: History, Status, and Taxonomy |url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/10.2984/70.1.8 |journal=Pacific Science |language=en |volume=70 |issue=1 |pages=115 |doi=10.2984/70.1.8 |issn=0030-8870}}</ref> 

The dawn song on the [[Mariana Islands]] is a "wheezy whistle"; on the [[Northern Mariana Islands]] it can be transcribed as "ee-zoo-zee-zoo-zee" or "zeeoo-ZEE-zoo-zee". The daytime song, most commonly heard in the early morning, is a simple and tuneful "per-mit-you".{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Sounds and Vocal Behavior § Vocalizations § Geographic Variation}} On [[Palau]], the calls are unlike those of the Mariana Islands populations and instead resemble those of the [[great crested flycatcher]] of North America; the Palau call may also be confused with that of the [[Micronesian starling]].{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Sounds and Vocal Behavior § Vocalizations § Geographic Variation}} 

== Distribution and habitat ==
The Micronesian myzomela is a permanent resident of the [[Caroline Islands|Caroline]] and [[Mariana Islands|Mariana]] islands.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Distribution}} It has not been observed moving between islands, but the short distances between some in a chain may still permit dispersal.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Movements and Migration}} It can be found in and on the edges of forests, including [[secondary forest|secondary]], [[Clinostigma]], [[mangrove]], and [[agroforestry|agroforest]] types. It also inhabits coconut plantations, [[coastal strand]], [[savanna]] brush, villages, towns, and gardens.<ref>{{Citation |last=Higgins |first=Peter |title=Micronesian Myzomela (Myzomela rubratra) |date=2020 |work=Birds of the World |editor-last=Billerman |editor-first=Shawn M. |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/micmyz1/1.0/introduction |access-date=2026-05-05 |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |language=en |doi=10.2173/bow.micmyz1.01 |last2=Christidis |first2=Les |last3=Ford |first3=Hugh |editor2-last=Keeney |editor2-first=Brooke K. |editor3-last=Rodewald |editor3-first=Paul G. |editor4-last=Schulenberg |editor4-first=Thomas S.|mode=cs1}}</ref>

== Behavior ==
With few exceptions, all [[Honeyeater|honeyeaters]] are [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Winkler |first=David W. |title=Honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) |date=2020-03-04 |work=Birds of the World |editor-last=Billerman |editor-first=Shawn M. |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/meliph3/1.0/introduction |access-date=2026-05-13 |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |language=en |doi=10.2173/bow.meliph3.01 |last2=Billerman |first2=Shawn M. |last3=Lovette |first3=Irby J. |editor2-last=Keeney |editor2-first=Brooke K. |editor3-last=Rodewald |editor3-first=Paul G. |editor4-last=Schulenberg |editor4-first=Thomas S. |mode=cs1}}</ref> The Micronesian myzomela is a weak flyer, usually only travelling at most 5 meters by flight. It primarily locomotes while foraging by flying or hopping.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Behavior}}

=== Breeding ===
The Micronesian myzomela nests year-round, and likely breeds year-round as well.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Introduction}} On [[Pohnpei]], eggs were recorded in nests from July to September. On [[Chuuk State|Chuuk]], eggs have been found year-round, with most nests dated to May–July and one to March. On [[Kosrae]], a nest with nestlings was found in April. During 1983–1984, newly fledged birds were recorded on Chuuk in March, on Yap in May, and on Kosrae in July.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Breeding § Phenology}} On [[Saipan, Northern Mariana Islands|Saipan]], nest-building has been observed in February in each year from 1988 to 1993, and seven nests were found there in 2003–2004: two contained eggs, two contained nestlings, two were empty, and the seventh was occupied by a female that prevented its contents from being checked.<ref name=":4" /> Courtship was observed on [[Aguiguan]] in May 1992, and newly fledged birds on [[Rota, Northern Mariana Islands|Rota]] in March 1982.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Breeding § Phenology}} On [[Guam]], courtship interactions was observed to take place throughout the year, at any time of day; they usually consisted of flights lasting for 20–30 seconds, where the male pursued the female along circular, vertical, or zig-zag paths, often touching wingtips. The male may utter quiet staccato notes during such flights.<ref name=":5">{{Cite journal |last=Jenkins |first=J. Mark |date=1983 |title=The Native Forest Birds of Guam |url=https://digitalcommons.usf.edu/ornithological_monographs/22/ |journal=Ornithological Monographs |publisher=[[University of California Press]], for the [[American Ornithologists' Union]] |issue=31 |pages=45-46 |doi=10.2307/40166770 |issn=00786594|jstor=40166770}}</ref>

On Chuuk, nests are most often found near houses that had flowering plants nearby. The nests are usually built less than 4.6 meters from the ground. They are typically in small trees with thick foliage, often on the edges of wooded areas or open areas.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal |last=Brandt |first=John H. |date=1962 |title=Nests and Eggs of the Birds of the Truk Islands |url=https://academic.oup.com/condor/article/64/5/416-437/5229497 |journal=[[Ornithological Applications|The Condor]] |volume=64 |issue=5 |article-number=6 |pages=433–434 |doi=10.2307/1365549 |issn=1938-5129 |via=[[Oxford University Press]]}}</ref> On Guam, nests were usually placed 1.2{{Endash}}2.4 meters off the ground, in shrubs or trees, and more rarely 2.5{{Endash}}4.6 meters off the ground, on the outer branches of trees.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Breeding § Nest Site}} There, nests had deep cups made of grasses and rootlets, withl the outside composed of leaves, wool, cobwebs, and the like. They were 50{{Endash}}70 mm deep and 60{{Endash}}80 mm wide.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Breeding § Nest}} On Chuuk, nests are usually composed of weed stems, bits of leaves, grasses, and [[coir]], and lined with fine grasses. On the outside, they are on average 20 mm deep, and 50 mm wide. <ref name=":2" /> On Pohnpei, nests are cup-shaped, and are made up of two layers{{Emdash}}the inner layer is composed of one material, such as dead grass, fine roots, or coir, however the exact material varies by nest. The outer layer is composed of a mix of stems, ferns, fine roots and the like. The inner and outer diameters of the nest are 65{{Endash}}85 mm and 43{{Endash}}58 mm respectively. Nests are around 20 mm deep, and measure 35{{Endash}}45 mm in height.<ref name=":3" />

These eggs are usually white and gray with dark yellow-brown speckles concentrated at the narrower tip.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Breeding § Eggs}} On Chuuk, eggs are on average 18.5 by 13.6 mm. They are glossy white or light cream with reddish-brown speckling concentrated torwards the larger end.<ref name=":2" /> On Pohnpei, eggs are white to pale creamy, with brown (sometimes with hues of yellow or red) spots on the surfaces. The subsurfaces of the eggs are pale purplish. Clutches are usually two eggs; in a sample of 13 nests, 10 had two eggs, and three had one egg.<ref name=":3">{{Cite journal |last=Yamashina |first=Yoshimaro |date=1932 |title=Micronesia-san Tōrui no Tamago no Shūshūbutsu ni Tsuite |script-title=ja:ミクロネシア産鳥類の卵の蒐集物に就いて |trans-title=On a Collection of Eggs of Birds from Micronesia |url=http://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/jjo1915/7/35/7_35_393/_article/-char/ja/ |journal=[[Tori (journal)|Tori]] |language=ja |volume=7 |issue=35 |pages=397 |doi=10.3838/jjo.7.35_393 |issn=0040-9480 |via=[[J-STAGE]]}}</ref> On Saipan, eggs are creamy white, with two distinct rings of brown spots on either end.<ref name=":4" />

On Saipan, [[egg incubation]] lasts for 15{{Endash}}16 days, and is probably done exclusively by females. Incubation behaviors resemble that of other honeyeaters.{{Sfn|Craig|Pyle|2026|loc=Breeding § Incubation}} At birth, nestlings are [[altricial]], and, until their red [[Pin feather|pin feathers]] erupt, resemble nestling [[Bridled white-eye|bridled white-eyes]]. In one nest, nestlings were around 2 cm in length, with dark pink skin and had down on their wings and backs. By day 6{{Endash}}7, their eyes started to open, and the pin feathers on their backs began to erupt. Both nestlings prematurely [[Fledge|fledged]] on days 13{{Endash}}14; one of them was returned to the nest, and fully fledged on day 15-16.<ref name=":4">{{Cite thesis|last=Sachtleben |first=Thalia |title=Predation and nest success of forest birds in native and non-native habitat on Saipan, Mariana Islands |date=2005 |url=https://mountainscholar.org/handle/10217/211855 |access-date=2026-05-18 |publisher=[[Colorado State University]] |language=en |doi=10.25675/3.020863 |last2=Savidge |first2=Julie A.|degree=M.S.|pages=79-83}}</ref> On Pohnpei, the female exclusively feeds the young.{{sfn|Baker|1951|p=308}}

On Guam, a female was observed [[feigning injury]], spreading her tail and quivering her wings, and made calls while hopping on a low-lying branch.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Stophlet |first=John J. |date=1946 |title=Birds of Guam |url=https://digitalcommons.usf.edu/auk/vol63/iss4/5/ |journal=[[The Auk]] |volume=63 |issue=4 |pages=540 |doi=10.2307/4079755}}</ref><ref name=":5" /> On Saipan, nesting adults become agitated when observed; one or both would feign injury, drooping one wing and fluttering close to the ground.<ref name=":4" />

